Missing Data practical Week 3

Kim Luijken, adapted from work by Valentijn de Jong and Thomas Debray

2022

This practical was developed using R version 4.1.1.

Introduction

You perform a cohort study on annual influenza vaccine effectiveness. The aim of the study is to assess whether annual influenza vaccination reduces the risk of hospitalisation. The data consist of observations on eligible subjects who did, or did not, receive the annual influenza vaccine. The endpoint in this study is hospitalisation during the influenza epidemic period. Note that the vaccine was not randomly allocated; rather vaccination status may depend on characteristics of the participants in the study.

Variable Description Coding Meaning
vacc Influenza vaccination 0 Unvaccinated
vacc Influenza vaccination 1 Vaccinated
age Age Continuous Years
sex Sex 0 Male
sex Sex 1 Female
cvd Cardiovascular disease 0 Absent
cvd Cardiovascular disease 1 Present
pulm Pulmonary disease 0 Absent
pulm Pulmonary disease 1 Present
DM Diabetus mellitus 0 Absent
DM Diabetus mellitus 1 Present
contact Number of GP contacts Discrete Count
hosp Hospitalisation status 0 No hospitalisation
hosp Hospitalisation status 1 Hospitalisation

Aim of the practical

The aims of the current practical are:

  • to get familiar with methods that handle univariate missingness, i.e., missingness in a single variable
  • to get familiar with methods that handle multivariate missingness, i.e. missingness in multiple variables

Preparation

The research question you will address here is whether influenza vaccination affects hospitalisation. As vaccination was not randomized, confounder adjustment is necessary. To investigate the effect of influenza vaccination on risk of hospitalisation, we will fit the following regression model:

formula(hosp ~ vacc + DM + cvd + pulm + I(log(contact)) + age + sex)

Univariate missingness

To learn about imputation methods, we focus on a univariate missingness problem first. To that extent, we load a dataset in which only data on cardiovascular disease is missing.

load("miss.data.uni.RData")

Question 2. Do you think the missingness was caused by a MAR or MNAR mechanism? Why?

Answer: There is no statistical test that can indicate whether data ar MAR of MNAR. The assumption of MAR of MNAR needs to be made by you as a researcher.

We are now going to perform multiple imputation to impute the missing values of cvd, using the mice package.

install.packages("mice")
library(mice)

MICE distinguishes between three types of variables: numeric, binary (factor with 2 levels), and categorical (factor with more than 2 levels). Each type has a default imputation method,: predictive mean matching for numeric data, logistic regression for binary data, and polytomous (unordered) regression for categorical data.

Indicate which measurement level each variable has to make sure mice handles them well.

MICE.data.uni <- with(miss.data.uni, data.frame(sex = factor(sex), 
                                              age = age, 
                                              vacc = factor(vacc), 
                                              cvd = factor(cvd), 
                                              pulm = factor(pulm), 
                                              DM = factor(DM), 
                                              contact = contact, 
                                              hosp = factor(hosp)))

We begin by performing a dry run for the multiple imputation procedure.

set.seed(28102022)

# Configuration of the MICE model
MICE.0.uni <- mice(MICE.data.uni, maxit = 0)

  • For each variable in the data set, an imputation model can be supplied. What model is to be used depends on the distribution of the variable. Misspecification of the imputation model may therefore cause implausible values to be imputed.

MICE - default

By default, mice() will generate 5 imputed datasets and perform 5 iterations in the Gibbs sampler. Please be patient, as this takes a few minutes.

MICE.imp.data.default.uni <- mice(MICE.data.uni, m = 5)

Of note, before we analyze the data, it is important to perform checks to inspect the imputation. There are multiple checks to conduct, but as a preliminary illustration, we provide code here to assess whether the Gibbs sampler converged by assessing the trace line plot.

plot(MICE.imp.data.default.uni, y = "cvd", layout = c(2,1))

We can now analyze the imputed datasets and store the results. We fit a logistic regression model in each imputed data set, and combine the results using Rubin’s rules. Note that when applying the with() statement to MICE.imp.data.default.uni, the glm() command recognizes this is a dataset with multiple imputations.

# Start the analyses
MIversion1.uni <- with(data = MICE.imp.data.default.uni, 
                   exp = glm(hosp ~ vacc + DM + cvd + pulm + I(log(contact)) + age + sex, 
                             family = binomial()))

# Use Rubin's rules
pooledEst.uni <- pool(MIversion1.uni)

The mice built-in function pool() provides information on the pooled regression coefficients (estimate), the within-imputation variance (ubar), the between-imputation variance (b), and the total variance (t).

Multivariate missingness

Multivariate missingness has major implications for most imputation methods:

  • the covariates that provide information on the missingness mechanism contain missing values themselves;
  • this “circular” dependence occurs even given information from other covariables;
  • especially with a large number of covariates with missing values and small sample size, collinearity or empty cells occur;
  • variables are of different types (e.g., binary, unordered, ordered, continuous), thereby making the application of theoretically convenient models, such as the multivariate normal, theoretically inappropriate;
  • imputation can create impossible combinations such as pregnant fathers.

For a description of the missing data patterns, revisit your results from last week’s practical. In this practical, we will use multiple imputation for this data with multivariate missingness

Load the data with multivariate missingness.

load("miss.data.multi.RData") # if the data is in your working directory
load(file.choose()) # if it is not

Indicate which measurement level each variable has to make sure mice handles them well.
